<paragraph id="F7691D17FFF7B54BAE37F4D4FC8E177A" blockId="11.[811,1420,204,930]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BAE37F4D4FA94169B" box="[813,1398,204,229]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" reason="1">
<taxonomicName id="30D66694FFF7B54BAE37F4D4FB65169A" authority="Peale, 1848" authorityName="Peale" authorityYear="1848" box="[813,1159,204,229]" class="Aves" family="Petroicidae" genus="Petroica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="multicolor">
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BAE37F4D4FBE3169B" bold="true" box="[813,1025,204,228]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Petroica multicolor</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="934760E6FFF7B54BA912F4D4FB65169A" author="Peale TR" box="[1032,1159,204,229]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" refId="ref15291" refString="Peale TR (1848) United States Exploring Expedition. During the years 1838, 1839, 1840, 1841, 1842. Under the command of Charles Wilkes, U. S. N. Vol. VIII. Mammalia and Ornithology. J. B. Lippincott &amp; Co., Philadelphia, 466 pp." type="book" year="1848">Peale, 1848</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, Pacific Robin: 
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BA82AF4D4FA94169B" box="[1328,1398,204,228]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,160,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[168,1419,160,1843]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (male). B. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (female). C. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor feminina. D. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor ambrynensis. E. Yellow-fronted White-eye Zosterops flavifrons. F. Island Thrush Turdus poliocephalus efatensis. G Royal Parrotfinch Erythrura regia." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Figure</figureCitation>
</emphasis>
4C, D
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F7691D17FFF7B54BAE48F517FB4215DD" blockId="11.[811,1420,204,930]" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">
The Pacific Robin is a widespread, polytypic taxon that occurs from the 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BA904F529FB341736" box="[1054,1238,305,329]" name="Solomon Islands" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Solomon Islands</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BA818F529FAAC1736" box="[1282,1358,305,329]" name="Samoa" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Samoa</collectingCountry>
. It is easily identifiable based on its tiny size and generally black-and-red plumage with pale forehead and wing patch. Only Cardinal 
<taxonomicName id="30D66694FFF7B54BA901F58DFB6F17D2" authorityName="Vigors &amp; Horsfield" authorityYear="1827" box="[1051,1165,405,429]" class="Aves" family="Meliphagidae" genus="Myzomela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Myzomela</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="30D66694FFF7B54BA9BAF58DFA6017D2" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1788" box="[1184,1410,405,429]" class="Aves" family="Meliphagidae" genus="Myzomela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cardinalis">
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BA9BAF58DFA6017D2" box="[1184,1410,405,429]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Myzomela cardinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is superficially similar in plumage, but 
<taxonomicName id="30D66694FFF7B54BA9CBF5AFFA8217B1" baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1788" box="[1233,1376,438,462]" class="Aves" family="Meliphagidae" genus="Myzomela" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cardinalis">
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BA9CBF5AFFA8217B1" box="[1233,1376,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">M. cardinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a relatively long, decuved bill, whereas Pacific Robin has a much shorter, straight bill. Its IUCN status is Least Concern. Five subspecies occur in 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BA963F603FB32144D" box="[1145,1232,539,562]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
and we recorded 3 during our survey. 
<taxonomicName id="30D66694FFF7B54BA93BF625FA82142B" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1934" box="[1057,1376,572,596]" class="Aves" family="Petroicidae" genus="Petroica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="multicolor" subSpecies="feminina">
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BA93BF625FA82142B" box="[1057,1376,572,596]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Petroica multicolor feminina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, so named because males have female-like plumage (
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BA87AF645FCAC14E8" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,160,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[168,1419,160,1843]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (male). B. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (female). C. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor feminina. D. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor ambrynensis. E. Yellow-fronted White-eye Zosterops flavifrons. F. Island Thrush Turdus poliocephalus efatensis. G Royal Parrotfinch Erythrura regia." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), is endemic to Éfaté; 
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BA92FF667FB1614E8" box="[1077,1268,639,663]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">P. m. ambrynensis</emphasis>
is widespread across central 
<collectingCountry id="8FC15D87FFF7B54BAED2F6B9FBFD14C7" box="[968,1055,673,696]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
(Malakula and Gaua on our survey; 
<figureCitation id="6FED0192FFF7B54BAE7BF6D9FC5414A5" box="[865,950,705,730]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="12.[168,230,1869,1889]" captionTargetBox="[169,1418,160,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[168,1419,160,1843]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 4. Photos of birds mistnetted during our survey of Vanuatu: A. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (male). B. Melanesian Flycatcher Myiagra caledonica (female). C. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor feminina. D. Pacific Robin Petroica multicolor ambrynensis. E. Yellow-fronted White-eye Zosterops flavifrons. F. Island Thrush Turdus poliocephalus efatensis. G Royal Parrotfinch Erythrura regia." pageId="11" pageNumber="766">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
); and 
<emphasis id="C5A2C105FFF7B54BAEEDF6DAFB8914A6" box="[1015,1131,706,729]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="766">P. m. soror</emphasis>
is endemic to Vanua Lava. We found Pacific Robins to be uncommon on Éfaté and Malakula and rare on Gaua and Vanua Lava. Individuals on Éfaté were vocal and specimens of males had enlarged gonads and seminal vesicles. A female on Gaua had 4 yolks (largest 
<quantity id="302EB0F2FFF7B54BAED0F771FBF215FE" box="[970,1040,873,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="766" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
). No specimens were molting and stomach contents were arthropods.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
